<m0>he Amazon region was densely populated when the first Europeans arrived in South America, yet fish, game and forests remained plentiful. A <m0>University of Florida <m0>geographer argues that powerful supernatural beliefs prevented indigenous people from depleting their area's natural resources.<ep>
  It was nothing close to Henry David Thoreau's notions about the virtues of living in harmony with the land, Nigel Smith said. Rather, profound fear of supernatural spirits kept greed in check. ``They believed there are spirit beings out there who will punish people who go overboard when they hunt and fish.''<ep>
  In two decades of research projects such as charting communities in the Amazon's flood plain and collecting genetic data on plants, Smith also collected folklore from peasants. His book, <m0>The Enchanted Amazon Rain Forest: Stories from a Vanishing World, <m0>has just been published by the University Press of Florida.<ep>
  He heard stories about spirit protectors of two dozen species of fish important in diets and commerce. He collected gruesome tales about what the ``Father of Game'' did to hunters who killed too many animals per hunting trip. Other stories of supernatural nature protectors include the ``Mother of Rubber Trees,'' who stole the shadows of rubber gatherers when they gashed rubber trees too much while gathering sap.<ql>
